<div id="review_1894671734" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1894671734" />
    <a title="Anirudh" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/16686132-anirudh"><img alt="Anirudh" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1359010972p2/16686132.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1894671734?book_show_action=true">Oct 01, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Anirudh" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Anirudh" href="/user/show/16686132-anirudh">Anirudh</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/16686132-anirudh?shelf=sci-fi">sci-fi</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1894671734" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7875656630949648404">Pandora&apos;s Star, being my first serious venture into science fiction was a lucky pick and did not disappoint. This is truly an epic space opera having a vast amount of characters, grand design, drama, action and of course science beyond imagination. I do not know if what the author explains is scientifically possible, but it is definitely thoroughly entertaining. <br/><br/><b>1. Plot</b> Without giving away too many spoilers, the story revolves around man&apos;s discovery of worm holes, a method to travel vast distanc</span>
  <span id="freeText7875656630949648404" style="display:none">Pandora's Star, being my first serious venture into science fiction was a lucky pick and did not disappoint. This is truly an epic space opera having a vast amount of characters, grand design, drama, action and of course science beyond imagination. I do not know if what the author explains is scientifically possible, but it is definitely thoroughly entertaining. <br /><br /><b>1. Plot</b> Without giving away too many spoilers, the story revolves around man's discovery of worm holes, a method to travel vast distances with ease and the subsequent exploration and colonisation of man. The story begins when man discovers 2 stars which have been sealed off by an unknown entity and his curiosity to know what lies beyond. Hamilton has a very interesting story to tell, a story that has multiple elements going well for it. (though not all) The sheer size of this story is daunting but equally enthralling. From the mysterious encounters with the aliens to the fighting clans of Far away the story has a wide variety of sub stories to offer. However some of the stories drag on and hinder the pace of the main story. It would seems all stories will connect at some point in the next book, for now we wait.<br /><br /><b>2. World Building</b> This is undoubtedly the strongest aspect of the book. Hamilton truly brings out a world where humans have spread out like a virus infecting every planet they come across, exploiting it and despite the abundance of resources bickering and fighting albeit in a more modern way. I don’t know if it was intended but as I read it I felt it was an interesting reflection on man and no matter how developed he gets he does not let go of his primitive instincts. <br /><br />Another concept that was really interesting was the fate of death. Science has changed the way man looks at death entirely, reducing it to somewhat of a temporary inconvenience. This, while being a fascinating concept had the risk of ruining the tension or fear from the story as any harm can be repaired. However Hamilton manages it well and at the end does indeed bring out the fear in men despite all their technological advancement and makes it believable.<br /><br />There is another interesting concept of SI the self aware artificial intelligence and it’s interaction with humans. There are of course much more Hamilton has to offer but one must read the book to discover them<br /><br /><b>3. Characters</b> Pandora’s star being driven mainly by the story does little to explore characters beyond what is required to continue the story. However one cannot find fault in this approach as character exploration would not have suited this style of storytelling. <br /><br /><b>4. Narration</b> Hamilton is not the best of narrators. His style is quite straight forward and lacks the charms of word play or wit. This is a book where story takes precedence over all else. He does manage to build up tension with the main story but that’s about it. The switch between the main plot and side stories do not transition smoothly, this is especially true for the detective’s story which throws off the momentum of the space exploration quite a bit. I did not mind the length of the book however, that was something the reader is aware of before he begins reading. <br /><br /><b>5. Aliens</b> I believe this requires a special mention. The main antagonist in the story is very unique and extremely well crafted. The first encounter with them is undoubtedly my favourite portion of the book. It is a sheer pleasure to read how two entirely different species react to the existence of the other. <br /><br />This is definitely a book worth exploring. Get your laser guns, jump on your spaceships and be ready to sail to infinity and beyond. <br /><br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="7875656630949648404" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


